This is very basic casting. You don&#39;t need to even use Generics.

    List&lt;String&gt; foo_list = new ArrayList&lt;&gt;();
    ArrayList&lt;String&gt; foo_list2 = (ArrayList&lt;String&gt;)foo_list;

Now you can call your method with `foo_list2`.

You could do the same thing with an Object.

    Object a = &quot;a string&quot;;
    String s = (String)a;

A method `public void check(String i)` would accept `s` but there would be a compile time error if you tried to call `check(a)`.

I remember from University that such a technique can be used to easily model weird distribution. It&#39;s called &#39;Rejection Sampling&#39;.

For example, if you want a number between 0 and 100, uniformly distributed except for e.g. 42, which should occur 10% less than any other number.

Then you would have an algorithm like this:

    while true:
      result = random.nextInt(100)
      if result != 42:
        return result
      else:
        // 42 is skipped in 10% of cases
        if random.nextInt(10) != 9:
          return result
        else:
          // do nothing, go back through the while true loop

So it&#39;s a valid technique, at least in academics.

For a more complex example, see this video: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=IUL0TOLYNLE

But in this case, there&#39;s only a 0.1 % of actually needing a repeat, and 0.0001 % change of needing 2 repeats.

But on modern systems, having a 50% chance of getting repeats, and limiting it at a 1000 repeats or so is probably not too bad.

Given you are creating 3 walls of length 5 in a 10x10 space then you&#39;ll always have a location to place a valid wall. So your approach will work fine.

If you change the number of walls it is not clear when you can get impossible configurations.

At what if you change a length? I would recommend creating a method to check if a point is valid.

    boolean isValidHorizontal( int[][] matrix, int x, int y, length ){
        int length = 5;
        if(y + length &gt; matrix.length ){
            return false;
        }
        for(int j = 0; j&lt;length; j++){
            if(matrix[y][x + j] != 0){
                return false;
            }
        }
        return true;
    }

Then you can filter you can filter all of the points. 

    int n = matrix.length * matrix[0].length;
    List&lt;int[]&gt; hPoints = new ArrayList&lt;&gt;(n);
    for(int i = 0; i&lt;matrix.length; j++){
        for(int j = 0; j&lt;matrix[0].length; j++){
            if( isValidHorizontal(matrix, i, j) ){
                hPoints.add(new int[]{i, j});
            }
        }
    }

And return a random valid one.

    if( hPoints.size() &gt; 0){
        return hPoints.get( random.nextInt( hPoints.size() ) );
    }

There is a trade off here. You have to scan everypoint and store it in a list. When you have a few lines, I would expect this to be slower than just randomly picking one. Once you have many lines, then this will be faster. Also, this lets you know if you have no possible choices.

